ribed—read PR, analyze with LLM, post inline comments, then post summary—this appears to be a single-pass orchestration rather than multi-step agentic reasoning. So System remains the appropriate minimum level, though Agentic or Workflow could apply if the implementation involves multiple LLM passes or reasoning steps.\n\nI should verify that each behavior's test description actually requires the minimum level claimed. For behavior 1, I need to confirm the agent only processes changed lines rather than the entire file—this requires Integration level since I can't mock away the analysis logic itself. For behavior 2, I'm checking that GitHub API calls use correct line numbers, which I can verify by mocking the API and inspecting the call parameters.\n\nHowever, behavior 2 might be achievable at Unit level if I'm only testing the line number calculation function in isolation. At Integration level with a mocked GitHub API, I can verify the full flow. The minimum to catch line number errors is Integration level. But there's a question about whether the test would also need to validate the API request format itself—if GitHub rejects the request structure, that might require System level testing with a real API.\n\nFor behavior 3, the core issue is whether the LLM can identify bugs in real code. This needs an actual LLM and real PR content, making it Agentic level. The distinction between Agentic and System here hinges on whether the failure is about the LLM's reasoning capability or the code analysis infrastructure—the LLM's ability to spot the bug is the primary concern.\n\nBehavior 4 tests synchronization between inline comments and the summary comment. It requires mocking the GitHub API to verify both outputs stay in sync, so Integration is the minimum. Behavior 5 goes further by using a real GitHub PR and actual LLM, requiring System level since it needs the real platform to validate the full workflow. ) for the orchestration to work end-to-end.\n\nNow I can structure the output. For behavior 1, the key is verifying the agent correctly scopes analysis to changed lines—this requires integration-level testing with a real diff and agent execution. For behavior 2, I need to confirm inline comments are placed at the right positions, which also requires integration testing to validate the GitHub API calls with correct line numbers.\n\nBehavior 3 demands agentic-level testing since it requires the LLM to actually identify a real defect in provided code. Behavior 4 checks consistency between summary and inline comments through mocked API calls to verify every finding has a corresponding comment. Finally, behavior 5 tests the complete workflow on a real GitHub repository to ensure all components work together end-to-end. to correct line numbers in GitHub's diff view\n- justification: Testing requires understanding how line numbers map from file to diff coordinates, and verifying the GitHub API is called with correct parameters. Integration level (mocked GitHub API with realistic diff data) is minimum to catch off-by-one errors or incorrect line mappings. System level would be needed if the failure involves GitHub's actual diff format or API behavior changes.\n\nBehavior 3:\n- description: Code analysis identifies a legitimate defect in a pull request\n- justification: Correctness depends entirely on the LLM's analysis capability and non-deterministic behavior. No mock or deterministic test can verify that the LLM will reliably identify bugs. Must use a real LLM with known-buggy code to measure detection accuracy.\n\nBehavior 4:\n- description: Findings reported in the summary comment correspond exactly to inline comments posted\n- justification: Requires verifying consistency between two separate outputs (inline comments and summary). A unit test of just the summary generation wouldn't catch if the summary logic diverges from what was actually posted inline. Integration testing with both components running together is the minimum needed to ensure the outputs stay synchronized.\n\nBehavior 5:\n- description: Complete PR review workflow executes end-to-end on a real pull request without user intervention\n- justification: Only a real GitHub environment can surface actual failures like authentication issues, rate limits, network problems, and permission constraints. System-level testing is necessary since integration tests with mocked APIs won't reveal these infrastructure-level failures.\n\nLooking back at the original behaviors, they're describing specific testing scenarios rather than justifications for test levels. The first two are about scope and positioning accuracy, the third about LLM analysis quality, the fourth about output consistency, and the fifth about end-to-end execution.\n\nFor behavior 1, I should reconsider whether unit testing could work. A unit test could verify that a function analyzing code only processes changed line ranges when given full file content and a set of changed ranges. However, the behavior statement \"The review input is scoped\" suggests this is about the system's overall input handling, not just an isolated function.\n\nTo properly test this, I'd need a diff showing changes at lines 50-70 in a 200-line file with issues scattered throughout (lines 1-10, 50-70, 190-200), then verify the agent only flags the changed section. This could be tested at unit level if isolating the range-filtering logic, but integration testing the full analysis pipeline with realistic data would be more reliable for catching the actual failure mode: the agent reporting issues outside the changed lines. A unit test would be fragile since it only covers one code path.\n\nHowever, the probability depends on code structure. If the analyzer cleanly separates diff parsing from analysis, a unit test of the analyzer function itself might suffice (0.2 probability). But if there's global state or side effects involved, integration testing becomes necessary (0.6 probability). System-level testing 